<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-692-249  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 692 249.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Moscow: IBM to support Soviet education.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (International cooperation).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Computer industrySoviet UnionEducationComputer-assisted instructionInternational Trade.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOSCOW: IBM TO SUPPORT SOVIET EDUCATION 12/03/90 MOSCOW, U.S.S.R., 1990 DEC 3(NB) -- An IBM representative and the USSR deputy Minister of Education haveappeared live on TV in prime time explaining the details of nationwide IBMeducational project that is already in progress.andM;The 40-minute show on the Educational channel, one of four channels availablein Moscow, concentrated on IBM's project (in cooperation with educationauthorities) to build 40 high-tech education centers around the country.andP;  Thefirst has opened in Moscow.andP;  &quot;Others will be located in the countryproportionate to the number of school-age children,&quot; Deputy Minister FeliksPeregudov said.andM;Service and support personnel for all these locations are being trained inMoscow.andM;According to IBM's Moscow office, the project was a result of PresidentGorbachev's last visit to the US.andM;IBM's representative said that people in Surut, Tyumen, one of Soviet richoil fields, bought 500 IBM machines to be installed in kindergartens.andM;&quot;This project is a good example of how this can be done.andP;  We can proudly showthese enthusiastic Soviet teachers at schools to some of our Americanpartners in similar projects.&quot;andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19901130/Press contact: Robert Dounwell, IBM Moscowoffice, phone +7 095 207-5597 fax +7 095 230-2733)</TEXT></DOC>